    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters April 16th with a lineup anchored by two high-upside plays against Ryan Weiss. **Mickey Moniak** (75.98) is our strongest start, benefiting from an elite matchup against a 7.36 xERA arm and a significant platoon edge that boosts his floor; we expect him to capitalize on the prime #2 spot. Similarly, **Tyler Soderstrom** (72.71) and **Vinnie Pasquantino** (72.92) represent our core offensive engine today. **Vinnie Pasquantino** thrives on a 14% dynamic platoon boost against K. Montero, while **Tyler Soderstrom** enjoys a rare 10% park factor bump, making both mandatory starts as we hunt for counting stats. While **Josh Naylor** faces a tougher test in Walker Buehler, his 74.15 score remains elevated by the SP's struggles with command (5.19 xERA), providing enough leverage to ignore the individual pitcher quality.\n\nThe stolen base scarcity strategy remains at the forefront of our decision-making, particularly with **Brice Turang** (65.73) and **Jose Caballero** (70.59). **Brice Turang** earns a specific bump due to the high probability of SB success against Corbin, while **Jose Caballero** benefits from both a favorable wind and an advantageous platoon against Suter. We are monitoring the lineups for **Luis Campusano** and **Kyle Karros** closely; **Kyle Karros** (50.20) narrowly made the cut as a marginal play due to the massive SP mismatch, whereas **Luis Campusano** (41.89) is hovering near our benching threshold. If the pending lineups shift **Luis Campusano** lower in the order, we may pivot to our deeper bench reserves like **Zach McKinstry** or **Alex Freeland** to protect our cap efficiency. Note that **Giancarlo Stanton** (63.18) remains a solid play, as the wind-out conditions at his park mitigate some of his platoon disadvantages against Suter, keeping his power ceiling firmly in play for our 5x5 run.",
